ters consider key issues in the political economy of internal wars, as well as how differing types of resource dependency influence the scope, character, and duration of conflicts. Case studies of Burma, Colombia, Kosovo, Papua New Guinea, and Sri Lanka illustrate a range of ways in which belligerents make use of global markets and the transnational flow of resources. An underlying theme is the opportunities available to the international community to alter the economic incentive structure that inadvertently supports armed conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aBallentine, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBallentine, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBray, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCater, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunaratna, Rohan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuáqueta, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLunde, Leiv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalone, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurshed, S. Mansoob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRegan, Anthony J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoss, Michael L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSherman, Jake, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSherman, Jake, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYannis, Alexandros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook packa